text:
Marks & Spencer has said a damaging cyber attack caused by “human error” will cost the company around £300 million, with the affects likely to last until July.

The high street retailer was targeted by hackers around Easter weekend and has seen issues with contactless payments, click and collect orders, empty shelves and the halting of all online orders.

Almost a month since the attack was first revealed, M&S is still not taking orders online, with one retail expert telling ITV News they expected this was costing the company as much as £3.5 million a day.

Marks & Spencer has revealed that some personal customer data has been stolen in the recent cyber attack, which could include contact details and dates of birth.
 
The British retail giant said personal information taken could also include online order histories, but added the data theft did not include useable payment or card details, or any account passwords.
 
M&S was hit by the cyber attack three weeks ago and is struggling to get services back to normal, with online orders still suspended.

text:
Retail giant Marks & Spencer has revealed that customer personal data has been taken by hackers after being hit by a damaging cyber attack.

Chief executive Stuart Machin said the data had been accessed due to the “sophisticated nature of the incident”.

Personal data that could have been accessed includes names, email addresses, postal addresses and dates of birth, according to M&S.

But the group stressed the data does not include payment or card details, or account passwords and is not believed to have been shared online.

Talk’s Ian Collins discusses the story with consumer expert from The Everyday Expert, Harry Kind.

Click here for more from Talk https://talk.tv

If you need any help visit: https://talk.tv/helplines

#marksandspencer #cyberattack
title: “No One’s Safe In This” M&S Customer Data Stolen In Recent Cyber Attack

This week Tom and Chris are joined by Chef and the King of Butter, Thomas Starker at The Butcher's Tap and Grill in Chelsea.


Straker rose to fame during Lockdown due to his 'All Things Butter' video series, sharing tips on how to make amazing flavoured butters. Since then he's opened his first restaurant in Notting Hill with 3 more spots coming later this year, he's also released his debut cookbook 'Food You Want to Eat' and launched his own flavoured butter brand.


Straker shares what it has been like rising to fame so fast and an embarrassing story about his work experience.


Straker chats about why eating seasonally is a real passion of his, the guys try some M&S jersey royal potatoes and asparagus cooked up by the kitchen and Tom tells us about the farms he visits as part of the Farm to Foodhall campaign with M&S.

text:
Say goodbye to fake lashes and hello to your own lash royalty . Our Queen of Lashes Serum is the ultimate growth treatment designed to strengthen, lengthen, and revive your natural lashes — safely and effectively.

 Whether you’re dealing with lash damage, thinning from age or hormones, or simply want to enhance your natural look — Queen of Lashes is your crown jewel.

 Have Questions? We’ve Got Answers. 
Here are the top 10 most asked questions about lash serums — answered honestly.

1. How does Queen of Lashes Serum work?
It delivers a blend of peptides, nutrients, and botanical extracts directly to your lash follicles to stimulate growth, extend the lash cycle, and strengthen lashes from the root.

2. How long does it take to see results?
Most users see noticeable improvement within 3–4 weeks, with full results in 8–12 weeks when used consistently.

3. Is it safe for sensitive eyes?
Yes! Our formula is ophthalmologist-tested and free from prostaglandins, parabens, and harsh chemicals, making it gentle for sensitive eyes.

4. Can I use it with eyelash extensions or false lashes?
Absolutely. It nourishes your natural lashes, even with extensions or falsies, and can help them stay strong under the glue stress.

5. Does it help with lashes damaged by extensions, glue, or curling?
Yes — Queen of Lashes is formulated to repair damaged lashes, bringing them back to life with restorative ingredients like biotin and panthenol.

6. Will it work if I’ve lost lashes due to age, hormonal imbalance, or sun damage?
Yes! It’s ideal for lashes affected by hormonal changes, sun damage, or aging. It helps regenerate weak or dormant follicles.

7. Are there any side effects?
Side effects are rare. Some users may experience mild irritation initially. A patch test is always recommended before full use.

8. How often should I apply it?
Apply once daily on clean, dry skin along the upper lash line—just like eyeliner. One stroke is enough.

9. Can men use it too?
Of course! Queen of Lashes is gender-neutral and works for anyone wanting longer, fuller lashes.

10. What happens if I stop using it?
Your lashes will gradually return to their natural growth cycle. Continued use helps maintain dramatic results.

 Key Benefits of Queen of Lashes Serum:

Clinically backed ingredients

Fuller, longer lashes without mascara

Safe for sensitive eyes & contact lens users

No prostaglandins = No darkening of eyelids or iris

Easy once-a-day application

‪@PositiveSpirits365‬ 

Welcome to something deeper. This is not just a post you scroll past, save, or swipe through. This is a sacred space — a digital sanctuary — crafted to help you come home to yourself.

7 Days to Reset Your Spirit is a self-guided reflection experience from Positive Spirits 365. It’s more than visuals, more than a caption, more than inspiration. This is a soulful journey designed to realign you with who you already are — worthy, whole, and becoming.

Each post in this series carries intentional reflections, affirmations, actions, and journal prompts. These are not quick-fix quotes. These are heart mirrors, meant to stir truth, invite stillness, and offer clarity.

You may feel called to pause the post, sit with a line, replay the words, or close your eyes and breathe. That’s not a detour — that’s the path. Healing is not a scroll. It’s a slow returning.

Let yourself go at your own rhythm. Let Day One hold you for three days if it needs to. Come back when your spirit is ready — not when the algorithm says so.

Here’s how to get the most from this experience:

✨ Engage deeply. Don’t just watch — feel. Reflect. Journal.
✨ Pause often. Let the words land before moving forward.
✨ Rewatch as needed. Each time, something new will rise to the surface.
✨ Save it. Your future self may need these words again.
✨ Share it. You never know who in your circle is holding on by a thread.
✨ Follow Positive Spirits 365 for more soul-led guidance and gentle reminders to keep going.

This post isn’t here for vanity metrics.
It’s here for you — for your becoming.
It’s here when you're ready to listen again.
And again.

Because your healing doesn’t need to happen fast.
It just needs to happen.
title: ️ This Is Not Just a Post — It’s a Spiritual Invitation

This Is Not Just A Game - Soap | Captain Price | Yuri | Emotional Soldiers Story (CALL OF DUTY) Ep5

In This Is Not Just A Game, experience the emotional journey of iconic soldiers Soap MacTavish, Captain Price, and Yuri from the legendary Call of Duty series. This emotional soldiers' story dives deep into the hearts and minds of these war heroes as they face unimaginable challenges, intense battles, and personal sacrifices.

The Call of Duty franchise has brought us countless hours of thrilling combat, but this video showcases the raw emotions and human side of these fearless warriors. From Soap’s loyalty, Captain Price’s wisdom, to Yuri’s complex past, every moment is packed with emotion and intensity. Watch as these soldiers fight side by side, making decisions that will change their lives forever.

If you’re a fan of Call of Duty, action-packed gameplay, and gripping military narratives, this emotional journey is a must-watch. Experience the true meaning of camaraderie, sacrifice, and survival through their eyes.

Don't forget to like, comment, and subscribe for more content featuring your favorite characters and unforgettable stories from the world of Call of Duty!

#CallofDuty #SoapMacTavish #CaptainPrice #Yuri #EmotionalStory #COD #SoldiersJourney #MilitaryAction #GamingCommunity #CallOfDutyFans #EpicGamingStory #ActionGame #MilitaryShooter

Campaign:
Action-Packed Campaign with Multiple Perspectives | Intense Gameplay & Heart-Racing Missions"

Dive into the gripping single-player campaign of this action-packed game, where you step into the boots of various characters, shifting perspectives throughout the thrilling storyline. Divided into three exciting Acts, each mission presents unique objectives, including intense combat, strategic planning, and high-stakes challenges. The HUD guides you with precise directions, while real-time damage visualization keeps you immersed in the heart of battle.

Your character’s health regenerates when you strategically avoid damage, adding an extra layer of strategy to every encounter. From defending critical locations against enemy squadrons to planting explosive charges, each mission keeps you on the edge of your seat. Alongside you are fellow soldiers, aiding you in your journey, though they won’t be following orders.

But that's not all—prepare for intense and immersive sequences, including a graphic terror attack scene, which you can choose to skip if you wish to avoid potentially upsetting content. A powerful narrative combined with dynamic gameplay, this title is perfect for fans of military shooters and intense action sequences.

text:
This Is Not Just A Game - Soap | Captain Price | Yuri | Emotional Soldiers Story (CALL OF DUTY)

In This Is Not Just A Game, experience the emotional journey of iconic soldiers Soap MacTavish, Captain Price, and Yuri from the legendary Call of Duty series. This emotional soldiers' story dives deep into the hearts and minds of these war heroes as they face unimaginable challenges, intense battles, and personal sacrifices.

The Call of Duty franchise has brought us countless hours of thrilling combat, but this video showcases the raw emotions and human side of these fearless warriors. From Soap’s loyalty, Captain Price’s wisdom, to Yuri’s complex past, every moment is packed with emotion and intensity. Watch as these soldiers fight side by side, making decisions that will change their lives forever.

If you’re a fan of Call of Duty, action-packed gameplay, and gripping military narratives, this emotional journey is a must-watch. Experience the true meaning of camaraderie, sacrifice, and survival through their eyes.

Don't forget to like, comment, and subscribe for more content featuring your favorite characters and unforgettable stories from the world of Call of Duty!

#CallofDuty #SoapMacTavish #CaptainPrice #Yuri #EmotionalStory #COD #SoldiersJourney #MilitaryAction #GamingCommunity #CallOfDutyFans #EpicGamingStory #ActionGame #MilitaryShooter

Campaign:
Action-Packed Campaign with Multiple Perspectives | Intense Gameplay & Heart-Racing Missions"

Dive into the gripping single-player campaign of this action-packed game, where you step into the boots of various characters, shifting perspectives throughout the thrilling storyline. Divided into three exciting Acts, each mission presents unique objectives, including intense combat, strategic planning, and high-stakes challenges. The HUD guides you with precise directions, while real-time damage visualization keeps you immersed in the heart of battle.

Your character’s health regenerates when you strategically avoid damage, adding an extra layer of strategy to every encounter. From defending critical locations against enemy squadrons to planting explosive charges, each mission keeps you on the edge of your seat. Alongside you are fellow soldiers, aiding you in your journey, though they won’t be following orders.

But that's not all—prepare for intense and immersive sequences, including a graphic terror attack scene, which you can choose to skip if you wish to avoid potentially upsetting content. A powerful narrative combined with dynamic gameplay, this title is perfect for fans of military shooters and intense action sequences.

The biggest players in the American auto industry are sounding the alarm for 2025: things are tipping towards disaster, and many auto companies are at risk of going under. 

Recently, one CEO has bluntly admitted that his company, which is one of the largest car manufacturers in the U.S. and the world, only has 12 months to live in the best case scenario. 

At the moment, multiple industry executives are resigning from their jobs as they realize there's little they can do to save struggling auto firms.

American car companies are not only coping with production challenges, but also losing sales and market share to Chinese manufacturers, and that's pushing domestic auto manufacturers towards “breaking point,” according to a new whitepaper published by the SAE Detroit Section’s Global Leadership Conference Committee this week.
title: This Is Not Just A Car Market Crisis: Big Automakers Are Being Destroyed Before Our Eyes

In This Is Not Just A Game, experience the emotional journey of iconic soldiers Soap MacTavish, Captain Price, and Yuri from the legendary Call of Duty series. This emotional soldiers' story dives deep into the hearts and minds of these war heroes as they face unimaginable challenges, intense battles, and personal sacrifices.

The Call of Duty franchise has brought us countless hours of thrilling combat, but this video showcases the raw emotions and human side of these fearless warriors. From Soap’s loyalty, Captain Price’s wisdom, to Yuri’s complex past, every moment is packed with emotion and intensity. Watch as these soldiers fight side by side, making decisions that will change their lives forever.

If you’re a fan of Call of Duty, action-packed gameplay, and gripping military narratives, this emotional journey is a must-watch. Experience the true meaning of camaraderie, sacrifice, and survival through their eyes.

Don't forget to like, comment, and subscribe for more content featuring your favorite characters and unforgettable stories from the world of Call of Duty!

#CallofDuty #SoapMacTavish #CaptainPrice #Yuri #EmotionalStory #COD #SoldiersJourney #MilitaryAction #GamingCommunity #CallOfDutyFans #EpicGamingStory #ActionGame #MilitaryShooter

Campaign:
Action-Packed Campaign with Multiple Perspectives | Intense Gameplay & Heart-Racing Missions"

Dive into the gripping single-player campaign of this action-packed game, where you step into the boots of various characters, shifting perspectives throughout the thrilling storyline. Divided into three exciting Acts, each mission presents unique objectives, including intense combat, strategic planning, and high-stakes challenges. The HUD guides you with precise directions, while real-time damage visualization keeps you immersed in the heart of battle.

Your character’s health regenerates when you strategically avoid damage, adding an extra layer of strategy to every encounter. From defending critical locations against enemy squadrons to planting explosive charges, each mission keeps you on the edge of your seat. Alongside you are fellow soldiers, aiding you in your journey, though they won’t be following orders.

But that's not all—prepare for intense and immersive sequences, including a graphic terror attack scene, which you can choose to skip if you wish to avoid potentially upsetting content. A powerful narrative combined with dynamic gameplay, this title is perfect for fans of military shooters and intense action sequences.

text:
Vivian and Josh had their friend James capture their reaction to watching their wedding films for the first time. They hosted a little watch party at their home after lunch with a few friends and family who also attended their wedding celebration. I don’t typically get to witness my couple’s reaction to watching their films, so this was a treat. There's nothing quite like seeing their genuine reactions to the music, the scenery and the narrative of the film I poured my heart into crafting. 

It’s easy to get wrapped up in algorithms and social media likes and wonder “is my work good enough?” Getting to watch Vivian and Josh’s reaction in real time was absolutely priceless, incredibly validating and a reminder of why I love what I do. This is not just a wedding film - it’s a legacy and a testament to their love that will live with them forever.

text:
Marks and Spencer has halted all online orders as disruption continues across its stores as a result of a "cyber incident" earlier this week.

In a statement posted to social media on Friday, the high street chain said: "As part of our proactive management of a cyber incident, we have made the decision to pause taking orders via our M&S.com websites and apps.

Our product range remains available to browse online.

We are truly sorry for this inconvenience." 
Customers reported difficulty in getting their click and collect orders over the Easter weekend and on Tuesday, the high street retailer apologised to consumers as it confirmed it had to make “minor, temporary changes” to its store operations to protect customers and the business.

text:
Retail giant Marks & Spencer has revealed customer personal data has been taken by hackers after being hit by a damaging cyber attack.

Cybersecurity expert, Graham Cluley, tells us ITV News how customers might be impacted.

Chief executive Stuart Machin said the data had been accessed due to the “sophisticated nature of the incident” but stressed that this does not include payment or card details, or account passwords.

In a social media post, Mr Machin said there is “no need for customers to take any action”.

“To give customers extra peace of mind, they will be prompted to reset their password the next time they visit or log on to their M&S account and we have shared information on how to stay safe online,” he said.

text:
M&S is still trying to resolve its technical and e-commerce issues a week after it was hit by a sophisticated cyber attack.

It's thought the retailer was hacked by a group of notorious cyber-criminals known as Scattered Spider, some of whom are believed to be English-speaking teenagers.

For more than a week, M&S has been unable to accept online orders and some shelves at stores are empty due to measures to manage the cyber incident.

text:
Marks & Spencer has ordered hundreds of agency workers at its main distribution centre to stay at home as it grapples with the unfolding impact of a cyberattack on Britain's best-known retailer.

Sky News has learnt that roughly 200 people who had been due to undertake shift work at M&S's vast Castle Donington clothing and homewares logistics centre in the East Midlands have been told not to come in amid the escalating crisis. The retailer's own employees have been told to go into work as usual.

Online orders have been disrupted since last week following an "extensive" cyberattack, although the retailer has provided few details of the nature of the incident.

text:
In April 2025, Marks & Spencer (M&S) suffered a significant cyberattack over the Easter weekend, leading to the theft of customer data and major disruptions to its operations. The breach, attributed to the hacking group Scattered Spider, exploited social engineering tactics to gain access through a third-party contractor. Tata Consultancy Services (TCS), M&S’s long-standing IT partner, is conducting an internal investigation to determine if its systems or staff were the entry point for the attack. The incident has resulted in an estimated £300 million loss in operating profit for M&S, with online services expected to remain affected until July.  ￼ ￼

This event underscores the critical importance of robust cybersecurity measures and the risks associated with third-party vendors.

#CyberSecurity #MarksAndSpencer #TCS #DataBreach #RetailSecurity #CyberAttack #ScatteredSpider
title: M&S Cyberattack: TCS Under Scrutiny Amid £300M Loss

text:
Marks & Spencer has suspended some meal deals due to ongoing disruption from a major cyber attack, now entering its third week.

The hack, linked to a teen ransomware gang, has hit stock systems, paused online orders, and caused shortages in stores. Shoppers at locations like Victoria Station have seen signs warning of limited availability.

Staff have reportedly resorted to using personal WhatsApp accounts to keep operations running. M&S is one of several retailers targeted, alongside Harrods and Co-op. Experts say the attack could cost the company tens of millions in lost sales.

Mike Graham speaks with security specialist, Will Geddes.

text:
BIG DAY ON THE FARM! They’re Off to M&S 
Today’s video is a milestone in our farming journey — we're sending off a group of 36 cows to Marks & Spencer! From the early morning prep to the final send-off, come behind the scenes and see the care, hard work, and emotion that goes into this huge step.

I’ll show you how we get the cows ready, what the process looks like, and talk about what it means to supply such a respected UK retailer. It’s a proud and bittersweet moment — and one you won’t want to miss.

But that’s not all…
⭐️ Curly Fries the cow gets a major upgrade — he’s moving into a spacious new shed where he can finally roam freely inside and outside! Watching him explore his new home is honestly the cutest moment of the week.

Learn how to calculate the average user time in CPU given data in milliseconds format using Python. This guide simplifies the process with practical examples and code.
---
This video is based on the question https://stackoverflow.com/q/66802820/ asked by the user 'Subhan Khaliq' ( https://stackoverflow.com/u/14370562/ ) and on the answer https://stackoverflow.com/a/66803496/ provided by the user 'Bijay Regmi' ( https://stackoverflow.com/u/8591711/ ) at 'Stack Overflow' website. Thanks to these great users and Stackexchange community for their contributions.

Visit these links for original content and any more details, such as alternate solutions, latest updates/developments on topic, comments, revision history etc. For example, the original title of the Question was: Find average user time in the user mode in CPU

If anything seems off to you, please feel free to write me at vlogize [AT] gmail [DOT] com.
---
Understanding Average User Time in CPU

If you have been working with performance metrics in computing, you might find yourself needing to calculate the average user time in CPU. This metric is crucial for understanding how effectively your applications are utilizing CPU resources. In this blog, we'll discuss a common problem and its solution using Python: how to compute the average user time given data in milliseconds format.

The Problem

Consider that you have a list of data that indicates how long tasks have been executing in a CPU user mode, represented as milliseconds. The specific format of the data includes prefixes and suffixes that can make direct calculations challenging. Below is the sample data you might encounter:

[[See Video to Reveal this Text or Code Snippet]]

Here, each entry in the list contains the format 0mX.XXXs, where X.XXX are the milliseconds that need to be isolated for further calculations.

The Solution

To find the average time from this list, we can follow a few organized steps using Python.

Step 1: Clean the Data

The first task is to remove any unnecessary characters from the string format—specifically the letters m and s. For this, we'll use the regex module in Python, which allows us to easily manipulate strings based on patterns.

[[See Video to Reveal this Text or Code Snippet]]

Step 2: Calculating the Average

Once we have our cleaned data in a list of floats, we can easily calculate the average by summing the list and then dividing by the count of the entries.

[[See Video to Reveal this Text or Code Snippet]]

Alternatively: Using Python's Statistics Module

If you prefer a more concise approach, Python’s statistics module offers an average function, which simplifies the computation:

[[See Video to Reveal this Text or Code Snippet]]

Conclusion

By following these steps, we can efficiently gather and compute the average user time in CPU from a list formatted in milliseconds. Whether you choose to clean the data manually using regex or leverage the statistics module, these techniques will help you analyze performance metrics with ease. Now you have a fundamental understanding of how to process and analyze user time data in Python!

This method not only saves time but also enhances your ability to make data-driven decisions in computing.
title: How to Calculate the Average Time in User Mode CPU Using Python

text:
In this Chesterfield then and now Im standing on High Street at its junction with Glumangate and Market Place looking east towards St Mary and All Saints church.
In the 1974 view the shops you can see are Tylers Shoes, Littlewoods, Macfisheries and Boots on the other side of High Street.
Macfisheries went into liquidation in 1983 and Marks and Spencer's who occupied the building to the right of it demolished is and expanded into a new building in its place which you can see in the 2025 view. In the 2025 view the shops are Carfactory, Primark
On the right in both views is the famous Chesterfield open market which dates back to 1165

Photo A taken : 1974
Photo B taken : 17th May 2025
Time elapsed : 51 years

Past & Present - in fading Photographs.
High quality resolution fading photos showing local scenes as they were and how they are today from exactly the same view point. Then and now, Now and then, Past and Present, Old and New, Before and After. Call it what you want, just try one and see the effect!

The presentations you can see here are the result of many hours of work put in by myself ensuring that the old and new photographs line up precisely, I don't publish any if I'm not 100% happy with the match. 

http://www.derbyphotos.co.uk/thenandnow/

Please note that the Then & now section on my website is currently in need of a revamp as they were all created back in 2005 using Flash and this is no longer supported so I will have to recreate all of my work again using a different method. In the meantime I'm publishing then on my YouTube channel like this one.

Best viewed on a large computer screen or smart TV as this is recorded in 4K resolution with great music so a real waste watching it on a small phone screen. Did you know you can cast it to your smart tv from the YouTube app?

text:
In the last few weeks, there’s been a dramatic rise in targeted cyber attacks that have struck at the heart of major UK firms. M&S, Coop and Harrods have all been hit, so have global names like Coinbase and Dior.

So what is going wrong? First off, a lot of companies are shooting themselves in the foot with dodgy infrastructure. If you have firms layering modern platforms on top of legacy systems, the result is a complex, fragile environment that is easy fodder for exploitation. 

Read more about the recent cyber attacks on major UK firms here

text: Following a recent attack on the retail giant Marks and Spencer, the store was forced to close its online retail operation for several weeks.  On the 14th of May the company started to release information about the nature of the attack - essentially through a technique called social engineering, criminals were able to get access to M&S employee security credentials, and then subsequently gain access to M&S's database and customer data.  Emily discusses the impact of this type of attack on the consumer and the thoughts about retail sectors' engagement in fighting scams and fraud in general.

Today’s video is a BIG one — I’m learning to drive new machinery (with a few near misses ) and we’re preparing 36 of our cows to head off to Marks & Spencer!

✅ My slightly chaotic first time behind the wheel of heavy farm kit
✅ A full day on the farm, feeding, mucking in, and making mistakes
✅ The process of checking passports, loading, and sending off cattle to one of the UK’s top retailers

Whether you're here for the cows, the chaos, or the countryside — there’s something for you in this one!

The Opening Trade has everything you need to know as markets open across Europe. With analysis you won't find anywhere else, we break down the biggest stories of the day and speak to top guests who have skin in the game. Hosted by Anna Edwards, Guy Johnson and Kriti Gupta. 

UK bonds fell and the pound gained after data showed UK inflation rose more than expected in April, leading traders to pare bets on further interest-rate cuts from the Bank of England. In the US Traders are betting that long-term Treasury yields will surge due to concerns over the US government's debt and deficits, fueled by President Donald Trump's tax-cut bill. And we cross to the Qatar Economic Forum. Powered by Bloomberg.

#MEAction UK fights for recognition, education, and research so that one day all people with ME (myalgic encephalomyelitis) will have access to rapid diagnosis, and compassionate, effective care. As people with ME, carers and allies ourselves, we campaign on the issues that are most pressing. Visit our website at meaction.org.uk or email uk@meaction.net.

For #MillionsMissing we present a series of readings from Moving Mountains.  Moving Mountains is not about overcoming or conquering, but about living with and connecting, shifting the reader’s attention to the things easily overlooked by those who move through the world untroubled by the body that carries them.

Have you ever wondered why your dog keeps checking on you?  It’s not always just about love! There’s actually a deeper reason why your dog continuously looks to you, and understanding it can strengthen your bond even more. In this video, we’ll reveal what it really means when your dog keeps checking on you and why this behavior might be more about their needs than you think.

Here’s what you’ll discover:
✅ Why your dog keeps checking on you, and what it says about their emotional state
✅ How dog checking behavior reveals trust, dependence, and even anxiety
✅ The important things to know about why dogs check in on you and what they truly need 

Whether it’s following you around the house, glancing up at you, or making sure you’re in sight, when your dog keeps checking on you, it’s a sign that they are trying to connect, and sometimes they’re seeking reassurance or comfort from you.

text:
M&S has been targeted in a cyber attack which has left it unable to process online orders or take contactless payments. Some experts predict it could be costing the company millions of pounds each day.

The notorious hacking group, Scattered Spider is believed to be behind the attack. A cyber security company has told Sky News the group is "one of the most dangerous and active groups" they are monitoring.

There've also been cyber attacks against Harrods and the Co-Op which are being investigated?

On today's Sky News Daily Niall Paterson talks to our science and technology reporter, Mickey Carroll, about Scattered Spider and what can be done to tackle cyber gangs.

Producer: Natalie Ktena 
Editor: Wendy Parker
title: What is going on with the retail cyber attacks?

text:
M&S Hacked by Teen Cyber Gang? Here's my take on it so far.

M&S has been grappling with a major cyberattack since April 21, making it the first in a wave of high-profile retail hacks attributed to the group Scattered Spider.

This highly active threat group — reportedly made up of teens as young as 16 — is believed to have breached M&S systems, stealing sensitive credential data (including the NTDS.dit file) and deploying ransomware across parts of their infrastructure.

The impact? 

A £700M + drop in market value and significant reputational risk.

What’s notable is M&S’s silence amid the storm — perhaps not out of denial, but because their teams (and partners) have been working around the clock to contain the fallout. Behind the scenes, there’s likely exhaustion, tough decisions, and constant pressure.

Scattered Spider uses advanced social engineering, from phishing to MFA fatigue attacks, and has also been linked to breaches at MGM Resorts and Caesars Entertainment.

This incident is a wake-up call:

Cybersecurity isn’t just an IT issue — it's a strategic, reputational, and operational risk.

Even the most established brands can be deeply vulnerable.

Silence ≠ inaction — often, it means hard work is happening behind the scenes.

Continuous investment in resilience, culture, and readiness is essential.

Anything extra you think I should be sharing? Please add it in the comments. 

 #CyberSecurity #MarksAndSpencer #ScatteredSpider #RetailBreach #CrisisManagement #InfoSec #DigitalResilience #CyberAttack #BoardroomRisk #MFAFatigue #cyberawareness #cyberprotection #cyberresilience

text:
Chris' seasonal twist on a classic pasta dish is packed full of festive flavours with turkey mince, parsnips and a warming dash of cinnamon to make it a perfect family meal at Christmas time.

Facebook:   / marksandspencer  
Twitter:   / marksandspencer  
Instagram:   / marksandspencer  

Prep time: 3 mins
Cook time: 50 mins
Serves 4

Ingredients
1 onion, finely chopped
2 parsnips, peeled and finely chopped
2 sticks celery, finely chopped
1 tbsp dried sage
1 pack (400g) M&S Select Farms Oakham Turkey Breast Mince 2% fat
1 chicken stock cube, crumbled
1 tbsp ground cinnamon
1 clove garlic, crushed and finely chopped
1 tin (400g) chopped tomatoes
400g wholewheat penne
20g M&S grated Parmigiano Reggiano, plus extra to serve

Method
1. Heat 1 tbsp olive oil in a large non-stick frying pan over a medium-high heat.
2. Add the onion, parsnips, celery and sage with a pinch of salt. Fry for 5 minutes until the veg takes on some colour then add the garlic.
3. Turn the heat up to high and add the turkey mince, stock cube and cinnamon. Season and fry for 5 minutes until the meat is browned.
4. Add the tomatoes, then fill the empty tin with water and add to the pan. 
5. Bring to the boil, cover loosely and simmer for 35 minutes, stirring now and again until a thick sauce forms. 
6. With 10 minutes remaining, cook the pasta for a minute less than the packet instructions recommend, then drain and stir into the sauce with a handful of parmesan and cook everything together for 1-2 minutes.
7. Serve with a scattering of parmesan.



A note from Chris:
“There’s something special about eating together as a family at Christmas time, and I love putting a festive twist on this classic recipe, with delicious M&S parsnips, a touch of cinnamon and succulent British Oakham higher-welfare turkey breast mince, reared by Select Farmers for M&S.”
title: Chris' Festive Bolognese | Feed Your Family | M&S FOOD

text:
Marks & Spencer Suspends All Online Orders After Major Cyber Attack
A severe cyber attack has forced Marks & Spencer to suspend all online orders, sending shockwaves through its digital operations. Orders through the M&S website and app stopped abruptly on Friday as online payment systems failed. The event highlights the rising threats retailers face from cyber crime. Customers and companies alike now wonder what this means for their security and shopping habits.

The Cyber Attack and Its Immediate Impact
The trouble started when M&S detected irregular activity on its online payment systems. The attack overwhelmed platforms supporting both website and app orders, causing immediate system failures. As a result, the company froze all new online transactions to limit further risks and prevent potential data exposure.

M&S issued a notice confirming the halt to all online sales. Current orders already in the system faced delays as the business scrambled to secure its infrastructure. Core business operations—like online fulfillment, order tracking, and payment processing—all came to a sudden standstill.

For customers, the disruption was immediate. Many found shopping baskets stuck in limbo, orders unconfirmed, or payments hanging. With digital shopping now a mainstay for many households, even a temporary breakdown causes major inconvenience. Many shoppers rely on online orders for groceries, clothing, and everyday essentials. The incident reminded everyone how much trust is placed in online systems—and how quickly that trust can be shaken.

Operational Fallout and Customer Reactions
The fallout extended across every part of the M&S digital experience. Even as technical teams worked to contain the attack, customer support channels surged with inquiries. Questions poured in about:

Unfulfilled or pending orders
Potential delays in refunds or deliveries
The safety of stored payment and personal data
How long the outage might last
M&S communicated actively on social media and through direct emails. The company issued apologies and offered updates but stopped short of giving timelines for full recovery. The language focused on security and caution, emphasizing that no risks would be taken with customer data.

Despite reassurances, anxiety grew on social platforms. Some customers expressed support for M&S’s decision to prioritize security. Others vented frustration about interrupted plans, especially those waiting for urgent food or gifts. Many worried about personal information, asking for updates and clear next steps.

Order fulfillment teams faced their own challenges. The halt left warehouses and logistical hubs with canceled or delayed pickups. Delivery services waited for green lights that never came. The domino effect of the payment system failure rippled through the supply chain.

Key concerns lingered:

How secure is the personal data stored with M&S?
Are financial details at risk?
When will normal online services return?
M&S promised to update shoppers regularly. The retailer also confirmed close coordination with third-party cybersecurity experts. Industry analysts watched closely, as company leaders weighed options for restoring service without making customers vulnerable.

Conclusion
The M&S cyber attack brought online retail to a grinding halt, forcing everyone to face the risks tied to modern shopping. The crash of payment systems exposed the fragility of key business functions. It left customers unsettled and businesses scrambling to maintain trust.

Events like this show that strong digital defenses are no longer a luxury—they are a necessity. Retailers, regardless of size, must anticipate cyber threats and prepare disaster plans. For shoppers, the hope is simple: that companies will keep their data safe and deliver on promises even when systems break down. Digital confidence is built on security. When that breaks, trust takes a long time to recover.

text:
Watch more at http://www.marksandspencer.com/MS-TV/... 

Today  we're making a chicken stir fry from three or four Simply M&S ingredients and this will give you a really tasty meal in under ten minutes. So the ingredients for this tasty chicken stir fry from the Simply M&S range are chicken breasts, mixed peppers, runner beans and fresh garlic. Heat a wok over a high heat. Add the oil and fry the garlic for around twenty seconds or until it's starting to colour. Add the strips of chicken and stir fry for four or five minutes until the chicken becomes golden around the edges. Now add the sliced peppers and runner beans to the wok and fry for a minute or two. Then add the spring onions and fry for a couple more minutes. Pour in the orange juice - bang on a lid and cook for a further minute. Check to make sure that the chicken is cooked through. Taste and season. Serve immediately with rice or noodles. Stir fry - a quick and delicious, everyday meal for the family using quality Simply M&S ingredients.

Find out more at http://www.marksandspencer.com/Simply...

text:
UK retail giant Marks & Spencer was paralyzed by a massive cyberattack, disrupting thousands of orders, crashing payment systems, and wiping out millions in market value. In this video, we break down everything that happened — from the first glitches to the ransomware threat, the hackers behind it, and where the crisis stands today.

 Learn how the Scattered Spider hacker group infiltrated one of the UK’s most trusted retailers using social engineering and ransomware.

 Discover the real-world consequences of a digital attack: food waste, canceled wedding cakes, broken returns systems, and manual operations in 2025.

 As cyberattacks on major corporations rise, this story is a wake-up call for businesses and customers alike.

 Subscribe for more breakdowns of the stories behind major global events, tech, and security.

text:
You loved our last shopping trip so we’re at it again! And if you’re a regular viewer of Friday Night Fashion (thank you!) you’ll know how impressed we are with the fashion renaissance happening at Marks and Spencer. So we thought we’d treat ourselves to good old mooch around one of their beautiful store in the iconic Battersea Power Station. We’ll style ourselves, each other and give you the lowdown on what to get your hands on in M&S now. Let us know what you think!

text:
️ M&S Cyberattack 2025: What Happened and How to Protect Yourself
In Spring 2025, Marks & Spencer (M&S)—one of the UK’s most iconic retailers—was hit by a major cyberattack that disrupted operations for over three weeks. From delays in online orders to the shutdown of contactless payments in stores, the breach caused widespread chaos for both customers and the business.

In this video, we analyze the full story, uncover the attackers’ motives, and break down how it happened. Most importantly, we share critical cybersecurity lessons you can apply today—whether you're a consumer, student, business owner, or IT professional.

 Video Outline
00:00:00 – From High Street to Online Giant
A quick look at M&S’s digital transformation journey before the attack.

00:00:37 – Chaos in the Aisles and Online
How the cyberattack crippled contactless payments and delayed customer orders.

00:01:15 – What Did They Take?
We explore the type of sensitive data compromised, including customer and employee information.

00:01:45 – Who Targeted M&S?
Insights into possible threat actors and motivations behind the breach.

00:02:31 – How Did They Do It?
A breakdown of the attack vector, including phishing, vulnerabilities, and system misconfigurations.

00:03:11 – A Costly Lesson
The financial and reputational damage M&S faced, and why it's a wake-up call for all businesses.

00:03:50 – M&S’s Response
What the company did to contain the breach, notify affected users, and prevent future incidents.

00:04:32 – Tips for Everyone
Actionable cybersecurity tips for both individuals and organizations—don’t skip this part!

00:05:14 – A Wake-Up Call
Final thoughts on how the M&S cyberattack reflects broader cyber threats in today’s digital world.

 Why You Should Watch
Whether you're working in tech, studying cybersecurity, or just shopping online—you are a target. This video gives you the tools to recognize threats and protect your digital identity.

 Like if you learned something valuable
 Share to raise cybersecurity awareness
 Subscribe for weekly cyber threat case studies & defense tips
 Drop your thoughts or questions in the comments!

Episode Guest

Stuart Machin, Chief Executive Officer at Marks & Spencer meets with Jack Parsons (Jackson) UK's Chief Youth Officer.

Stuart is the Chief Executive of M&S. He took over as Chief Executive Officer in May 2022, having joined M&S as Food Managing Director in April 2018 with 30 years’ experience across food, fashion and home retail sector.

Prior to his appointment as CEO, Stuart was joint Chief Operating Officer, where in addition to leading M&S Food, he also took responsibility for property and store development, store operations, HR and IT.

Stuart is also a director of Ocado Retail Limited – the joint venture between M&S and Ocado Group. Throughout his career, Stuart has held senior operations and commercial roles across the UK and internationally, starting his career in Sainsbury’s and British Home stores, Tesco and then Asda. Stuart spent 10 years in Australia as part of Wesfarmers as COO and CEO of Coles supermarkets and Target department stores respectively. Returning to the UK he was briefly CEO of home retailer and manufacturer Steinhoff UK.

Stuart has extensive experience of retail transformation and a deep understanding of operations, trading, marketing and online. He also attended the three-month residential HARVARD AMP programme in 2013 and the Harvard CEO programme in 2023.

text:
This week Chris shares his delicious spin on a Thai red curry, packed full of colourful veg and bursting with flavour, with sweet potatoes, beansprouts, baby corn and perfectly in-season sprouts.

Facebook:   / marksandspencer  
Twitter:   / marksandspencer  
Instagram:   / marksandspencer  

Prep time: 2 mins
Cook time: 15 mins
Serves 4

Ingredients
4 sweet potatoes, diced into 2cm pieces 
1 pack (180g) M&S 4 Thai red curry paste shots
1 lime, zest and juice
½ tin (200ml reduced fat coconut milk
1 pack (200g) M&S baby corn and mixed vegetable selection, veg cut in half
300g beansprouts
500g brussels sprouts, roughly chopped
2 packs (250g) M&S microwave basmati rice
200ml water


Method
1. Heat 1 tbsp olive oil in a large non-stick frying pan or wok over a high heat.
2. Fry the sweet potatoes for 3 minutes until lightly golden
3. Add the Thai red curry paste shots and cook for 2 minutes, stirring constantly
4. Stir in the coconut milk with 200ml of water and lime zest and bring to the boil
5. Add the baby corn and mixed vegetables and brussels sprouts, and simmer for 5 minutes
6. Add most of the beansprouts, saving a few to garnish
7. Mix in the juice of half the lime, then cook for another minute
8. Serve with rice and finish with an extra squeeze of lime juice and the remaining beansprouts



A note from Chris:
“A Thai red curry is a real favourite of mine, and here I’ve given it a twist with sweet potatoes, beansprouts, baby corn and perfectly in-season sprouts – grown in Lincolnshire by M&S Select Farmer George Read, which add amazing colour and flavour.”
title: Chris' Fragrant Thai Red Curry | Feed Your Family | M&S FOOD

text:
The recent ransomware attack on Marks & Spencer (M&S) is a sobering example of the evolving cyber threat landscape confronting the retail industry. In this episode, we unpack how one of the UK's most iconic retailers fell victim to a sophisticated cybercriminal group known as Scattered Spider. This group, recognized for its advanced social engineering tactics, reportedly infiltrated M&S systems, stole customer data, and encrypted critical VMware ESXi infrastructure—disrupting store operations, wiping out millions in online revenue, and shaking investor confidence.


We dive deep into how threat actors like Scattered Spider gain initial access—leveraging phishing, SIM swapping, MFA fatigue, and vishing—to breach even mature IT environments. The attackers exploited Active Directory and targeted virtual infrastructure, maximizing both disruption and ransom leverage. We also explore the anatomy of modern ransomware campaigns and how social engineering remains the single most effective tool in a hacker’s playbook.


Beyond the breach, we discuss why retail is now the fourth most targeted sector, what technical and organizational defenses could have prevented this, and the regulatory consequences businesses face after a data leak. From the need for modern Active Directory security to the importance of incident response and breach notification protocols, this episode offers a comprehensive analysis—and practical takeaways—for CISOs, IT leaders, and security professionals across all industries.
title: Checkout Chaos: Inside the £3.5 Million-a-Day M&S Cyber-Shutdown

text:
His modelling career has taken him from Essex to a 50ft billboard in Times Square, but in his spare time, David Gandy loves putting his foot down.

There are classic cars, and then there are classic Jaguars -- so driving a 1959 Jaguar XK120 around the iconic Goodwood circuit is a pretty good day for me. There's nothing quite like it: the smell of the leather, the wood, the fuel... It's just astonishing -- there's a very romantic feel to it. Although, at 6'3", I don't fit into the car too well -- my knees are up to my nose and my head sticks up above the windscreen, which is a little disconcerting, especially if you've ever rolled a car (which I have).

I'm a complete petrolhead. My love of motoring was already well established by the time I bought my first car, a 1.1 1988 Fiesta Ghia, complete with electric windows that would only open if you pressed the button and simultaneously banged on the door. My friends and I nicknamed it 'The Beast'. I clearly remember taking a girl on a date in it; both the doors broke and she had to climb out through one of the windows. It's probably not surprising that I never saw her again.

My fantasy car, though, is a Jaguar XKSS -- there were only 16 ever made. They would have made more but the factory burnt down and production ceased. I actually got to drive one of them last year, but I don't think I'll ever own one -- they cost about £20 million each! Truthfully, I was a bit scared to drive it at first; I didn't want to be the guy that crashed the £20 million Jag, but it's essentially a racing car, so it drives better the faster you go. When I was

driving it, my earpiece may have accidentally fallen out, so I may have done a couple of laps a bit faster than I was supposed to. They ended up having to send a car out to come and get me, which was a bit embarrassing.

It wouldn't have been my first crash, though. Predictably, I've crashed a couple of cars racing, although in the last one I was actually the navigator and Yasmin Le Bon was driving -- we were partnered in the 2013 Mille Miglia, a 1,000-mile car race in Italy. My most notable crash -- purely because my dad never lets me forget it -- was when I crashed a tiny Peugeot. I went down a grassy bank and put the car on its roof -- even now, whenever I say farewell to my dad, he says, 'Drive safe, David. Mind those grassy banks.' I'm, like, 'Dad, it was 14 years ago, forget about the grassy bank' -- but you learn from your mistakes.

It's funny, most of my style icons -- people like Steve McQueen and Paul Newman -- are petrolheads too. My personal style is very utilitarian. I like quality outerwear, trousers and driving shoes; it's all pretty simple stuff -- exactly like James Dean, who almost invented the wearing of a white T-shirt. I think you have to find your own style; I'm not a big believer in trends. My advice is to always try different things, it's good to be individual, but finding what works for you and your look is the key. Just because something's on a runway or in a magazine, don't think it's the be-all and end-all -- if it doesn't work for you, don't wear it.

Read the full story at http://www.marksandspencer.com/s/styl...
title: M&S In the Moment With: David Gandy - 2014

text:
A severed leg on a cold, muddy beach is how it begins❗ No romance❗ No second chances❗ Just a brutal find that will haunt this jury for the rest of the trial❗ This is the First Date Murder Trial — and the State wasted no time dragging everyone into the dark❗

Day 1 of the First Date Murder Trial opened with unforgettable testimony from three key witnesses who each played a role in the discovery of a dismembered human leg along Milwaukee’s Lake Michigan shoreline❗

 Osyrus Terrell, a civilian, testified that he and a friend were walking the beach at Waramont Park when they found the leg❗ At first, they thought it might be from a mannequin❗ But the pink toenail polish and the fresh condition told them otherwise❗ They called 911 right away❗

 Officer Zachary Desmet of the Kad Police Department took the stand next❗ A trained evidence technician, Desmet described the scene as remote and treacherous — steep terrain, crashing waves, and erosion everywhere❗ He had to physically move the leg multiple times to protect it from being washed away❗ His testimony emphasized the leg’s fresh condition, lack of decomposition, and clean severance — details that drew grim attention from the jury❗

‍✈️ Finally, Deputy Leon Martin of the Milwaukee County Sheriff’s Office walked the jury through his bodycam footage❗ He confirmed the leg’s location — 10 to 15 feet up from the shoreline — and reinforced that no blood, drag marks, or related tools were found❗ The leg appeared placed❗ Positioned❗ Intentionally displayed❗

 How This Helps the State
The prosecution planted its flag in certainty❗ This wasn’t a mystery leg washed ashore — this was a statement❗ By opening with these three witnesses, the State reinforced that this was no accident and no random discovery❗ The leg was placed❗ The jury was told in no uncertain terms: someone did this, and they meant for it to be seen❗

 How This Helps the Defense
The defense raised tough, logical questions❗ If the area was so hidden, how did a casual beach walker find the leg❓ Why was there no blood❓ No drag marks❓ No saw, no knife, no axe❓ And why did the lead officer move the leg multiple times, potentially contaminating the crime scene❓ The jury heard one undeniable fact — no other body parts were found❗ No timeline was locked❗ No trail led back to the accused❗

⏱️ Check Out These Key Moments
 00:11 ➡️ Osyrus Terrell describes finding the leg
 06:02 ➡️ Officer Desmet testifies to beach conditions
 10:11 ➡️ Body part described in graphic detail
 14:15 ➡️ Desmet confirms lack of decomposition
 21:48 ➡️ Deputy Martin’s bodycam begins
️ 24:29 ➡️ Waves crash as leg’s location is confirmed
❌ 30:55 ➡️ No other evidence recovered
 35:05 ➡️ Court breaks after Day 1’s brutal opening

❓ Questions Raised
 Why was there no blood or drag trail if the leg was placed there❓
 How did civilians stumble across something so “hidden”❓
 Why did the officer move the leg multiple times before forensics arrived❓
 If the scene was deliberate, why wasn’t more evidence present❓
 Where is the rest of the body — and what connects it to the accused❓

text:
Share our wine adventure at: http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/food...

Our winemakers are truly passionate about wine and want to share their knowledge to help you explore and share in our wine adventure.

Subtitles
At M&S we're truly passionate about wine and to that end 
we're uniquely placed because we have team of winemakers in house. 

I'm Jeneve Williams and I'm a winemaker at Marks and Spencer. I'm originally from New Zealand and I trained as a winemaker in Australia. I do have some specialties. I look after New Zealand so within that my specialty would be Sauvignon Blanc. Sauvignon 
Blanc please. Thank you. We're trying to select the very 
best wine we can. 

We always blend our own wines from what the suppliers have. We select from different tanks and put together a blend for each wine so that we can have the very best expression of the harvest and so that 
we can have good consistency and stick to the style that our customers are expecting. 

I'm Sue Daniels and I'm one of the winemakers at Marks and Spencer's and I've been at Marks and Spencer's for thirty years. I just love the variety that there is in wine and the people that you meet. I don't know of another industry that I've worked in where 
people are so passionate about the product that they make 
and the land that they use to grow the grapes on. 

I'm Belinda Kleinig and I'm a winemaker at Marks and 
Spencer; I work in the wines team. I've been with M&S for 
four and a half years. I love that it's such an artisan product. It's different every year, every vintage is different, every wine is different, it's exciting, it's always changing, it's a very dynamic industry and I love the product. I love drinking wine. We travel a lot. We travel an 
awful lot to all the wine regions in the world always at the 
end of harvest, to cherry pick the best tanks for our 
customers. 

My philosophy on enjoying wine is to explore different styles of wine all the time. That's the exciting thing about the wine industry is that there's so many different types available. Take a risk sometimes and buy something that you haven't heard of before because you'll 
likely very pleasantly surprised.
title: Winemakers - M&S 2014

text:
Chris Baber shares a delicious way to enjoy sprouts on Christmas day, with smoky pancetta and walnuts bringing amazing, festive flavour to this seasonal veg.

Facebook:   / marksandspencer  
Twitter:   / marksandspencer  
Instagram:   / marksandspencer  

Ingredients:
• 500g brussels sprouts, sliced in half
• 65g pancetta
• 20g walnuts, finely sliced
• 20g sage leaves, roughly torn
• 10g butter

Method:
• Place the sliced sprouts in some salted boiling water for around 3 minutes, then drain and place in a bowl. 
• In a large frying pan over a medium-high heat, add the pancetta and fry for 3-4 minutes before adding the sage leaves and half of the walnuts. 
• Add the sprouts with the butter and cook for a few minutes then serve with the remaining walnuts.
title: Chris' Perfect Christmas Sprouts | M&S FOOD

Partywear: Sequined dresses, metallic shirts, and slip skirts perfect for festive events.

Bags and Accessories

Sequined top-handle grab bags for parties.

text:
Operating on an amended schedule, Aurizon Intermodal 2AD1 operated out of Adelaide, 10 Hours later than usual, leaving in the morning and operating through a big part of the state in daylight compared to its usual night run. This allowed for many shots at spots which usually sees the train passing through in the dark. 

GWA002 & CLF6 are in charge of the Freight Train, which is operating nearly 3000 kilometres through Central Australia from Adelaide to Darwin via Alice Springs, taking containers full of supplies and fuel for the remote outback townships. 

The train is seen at seven locations between Crystal Brook and Tarcoola, as seen below.

In this episode, we make our way to the magical town of Glastonbury! After exploring the quirky streets and soaking up the mystical atmosphere, something amazing happened — we were spotted by a viewer! As a thank-you, we gave away our very first subscriber T-shirt right there in town.

We then hiked up to the iconic Glastonbury Tor, taking in the stunning views and reflecting on how far we’ve come in our van life journey. Join us as we explore, connect with our community, and enjoy one of the most spiritual spots in the UK.

Don’t forget to subscribe — you could be the next person to spot us and get a T-shirt!

Welcome! We're Martin and Shirley, a married couple who started our channel in December 2024 when we made the bold decision to sell everything we owned and move full-time into our self-converted Renault Master campervan. Our goal? To break free from the grind of traditional living — no more rent, no more endless bills — just the open road and new adventures and most importantly - TIME.

If you'd like to support our journey and help keep us on the road, we'd be incredibly grateful! Your generosity goes directly toward essentials like diesel and keeping our adventures going. Every little bit helps, and we truly appreciate it. [ https://buymeacoffee.com/mnsvanlife ]

text:
The National Crime Agency (NCA) has named the notorious cyber-criminal collective Scattered Spider as a key part of their investigation into a recent wave of cyber attacks on UK retailers.
 
M&S has been hit with ransomware, which has scrambled the company's servers rendering computer systems useless, while a huge amount of customer and staff data was stolen and held ransom from Co-op. 
 
The group of hackers is believed to comprise young people, some of them teenagers, and are known to be native English speakers.
 
There has speculation they have been involved in the UK retail hacks - but this is the first time the police have confirmed that possibility is being actively investigated.

text:
The global gold market is experiencing growing pressure as central banks and institutional investors accelerate their shift from relying on paper contracts to securing physical gold, signaling a rising demand for concrete ownership amid doubts about the stability of financial instruments. According to Andy Schectman, president of Miles Franklin Precious Metals, this shift represents a fundamental change in financial behavior that hasn't been seen in decades and may indicate a wider erosion of confidence in the existing monetary system. Over 40 central banks have recently repatriated their gold from key Western vaults, such as the Bank of England and the New York Federal Reserve—locations historically seen as secure. In the United States, which was once a net exporter of gold, monthly import volumes have surged. This steady accumulation, Schectman argues, may reflect the early stages of gold's remonetization as a hedge against systemic risk.
